With respect to subsidiary financial statements requiring Jim Derrick's sig=
n-off, the internal accounting officer and the internal lawyer representing=
 the subsidiary company must initial the documents Jim is being asked to si=
gn;  they are then sent to me (I also initial anything that Jim signs that =
relates to Arthur Andersen, per Jim's request).  Jim and I are not CPAs and=
 we have little to do with the day-to-day operations of most of these compa=
nies, so that is the reason for all the diligence.  It is the responsibilit=
y of the general counsel of the subsidiary operation whose financial statem=
ents are being audited by AA to ensure that the proper review and initials =
are on these documents before they come to your group or mine----if not, we=
 send the documents back to them to get the necessary initials.  If you hav=
e any problems with anyone who delivers these documents to you, let me know=
 and I will be happy to educate them about this policy.  Bottom line for Ji=
m and me:  We have little knowledge or expertise when it comes to the prepa=
ration of the financial statements of these companies, and we are relying o=
n the expertise of our internal accountants who are involved in such prepar=
ation----they need to take "ownership" by initialing the documents.   Thank=
s for your help?.I hope these procedures don't make your job any harder tha=
n it already is!.   Regards, Rex.

